column3:
Your coverage of Genetic Engineering and Genetic Modification in agriculture has been poor. Three articles (Cavendish, June 19th; Kuyper, September 2nd; and Cavendish, again, October 2nd. Bit of a pattern there you think? Bit of balance needed?).
All these articles were pro- abandoning EU regulations in this area, all were pro-GM/GE, all were by non-specialists, and none seriously addressed the case against those technologies.  You should do better.  I can get stuff like this in the Daily Mail for a lot less than I pay you guys, and in the pub for free.

Thank you

column3:
More honest reporting on climate policies that are currently presented in a very biased and politically-oriented manner, as if science ever was about a consensus. Can you start reporting on the numerous scientists who do not agree with the supposed consensus? Can you inform the public about the true cost of net zero and how little an impact on climate it would have? Can you start reporting on the science articles that are in conflict with the notion that CO2 is a significant element in the trends of earth's climate? Can you start reporting on the articles that are getting released on the albedo effect? 

Can you also start reporting on the anti-democratic, anti-West and anti-capitalism stance of most of these left-wing policies? Perhaps you should refresh everyone's memories by re-publicising the writing of Sozhenitsyn (Warning to the West) and Milosz's Captive Mind for people to start realising what is at risk nowadays. The West needs to find the courage to be proud of itself and its history and if we are to allow the entire world to progress.

I need to see crypto in context, the bigger picture. I'm not interested in making a quick buck.

I would welcome more conservative opinions, to have "battles of ideas". Right now the conservative views are often attributed to various freaks, but in many areas to have healthy scepticism voiced in mainstream 
media would only benefit. Right now we talk about net zero, with only little attention given to the fragility of power mains, scarcity of rare/precious metals. Similarly we take for granted that change in climate is solely driven by CO2 without giving appropriate credit to excessive land use, water vapour cycle, acidification of the oceans.

column3:
I think FT writers need to cover Tech and FinTech in more depth.  So many articles on these firms focus on the fact they are highly valued despite making an accounting loss without really understanding what drives valuation of growth companies.  As a consequence you miss the real story on quality of growth, execution and delivery (be it good or bad).

Not a point on content, but it's a shame that your e-Paper renders in very low resolution, so isn't nice to read.  Compare it to publications on apps like Readly and you'll see what i mean.  The Guardian (for free) on Readly looks better than my FT e-Paper version....tragic!!!

column3:
While I am quite happy with FT's content and journalism in general, and I very much appreciate your coverage of the Green Economy as it is unfolding ...
It is sometimes amusing for me as a "mainland European" to see the British view of things, especially around Brexit. Sometimes it's not easy for the reader to understand whether a given article is from "FT, the worldwide newspaper" or from a "FT, the British newspaper".
I cannot offer solutions, but sometimes a clearer labelling of that distinction might help? Just for your consideration ;-)

column3:
Greater depth in trade, climate change, political economy, and tech regulation.  Much less on crypto, a totally meaningless market with very few implications.  

At a very high level, I want to understand *who* (what players) are invested in the global shift toward authoritarian capitalism; *how* countries can find common ground on global tax harmonization, climate change regulation, and other common policy goals; and *who* is leading the backlash against those urgent priorities.

Policymakers have shifted away from thinking about ensconcing or encasing the market from democratic forces as they did from the '80s through the '00s.  Now, to tackle climate change, low secular growth, the pandemic, and so on, the focus has shifted away from setting up transnational markets, and toward global solutions that do not destabilize the political and economic elite.

column3:
Good question. 

For me, at first glance, it is perhaps more of a format issue (the medium is the message?) 1. FT Videos need to be more accessible.; 2 More integration of podcasts ; 3. The infinite scroll + circles at the top of the FT app are fine but I worry I am less exposed to regional content than I was previously, including Africa coverage. 

I think the FT needs even more China overage. It has a lot but probably has more articles about the UK than China, which makes no sense given their relative weights in global GDP (on a nominal or PPP basis).

The FT movies and series of the week reviews are shocking. It is very British centric. And the reviews are always 5 stars for utter rubbish. Mind boggling. Book reviews are always stellar, of course.

I'd like a bit more critical analysis of US economic policy. We are int he midst of an enormous experiment across a range of policies and sectors, much of which are fairly nostalgic backward looking ones, often undertaken on the basis of one or two academics views, e.g. Phillipon and a few others on competition. Should econ policy really be driven by a handful of incectuous academic papers? We saw how that turns out when using reinhart and reinhart's 90% of GDP tipping point for sovereign debt --> austerity apologists.

Rana is great but somewhat of an old-school Keynesian nationalist cum industrial policy (Frierich List). More critical analysis of the left (i.e. Biden administration), from the left is urgently needed. And I don't mean Larry Summers and Olivia Blanchard and that old bunch. I mean clever Piketty-esque and Branko Milanovic angles, i.e. from a globally integrated view, on the basis of growing inequality. And the impact this has on the sustainability and efficacy of Biden's often inward looking policy solutions.

We are living in a remarkably bi-polar world within and between countries. I would love more critical examination of this, beyond 'the new cold war' and 'the relative decline of the usa' (is it or is it not declining blah blah zzzz - enough). Q Annon took the USA by storm. What have we done to better examine and understand where it has gone post-Biden? How has it morphed in Europe and impacted vaccine efficacy? What role has Russia played in this? Can Biden's policies succeed without support from Europe? etc.

column3: I would like to see the FT doing more to expose the hypocrisy in much of the rest of the UK print media. Secondly, and not unrelated, you should be ruthless in exposing the corruption in what one of your contributors referred to as the gilded chumocracy that now passes for government in the UK. These things should not be left to things like the Good Law Project and Private Eye to expose.

column3: I actually like the broad range of topics covered. When I first started with the FT around 1970 I felt all articles were very factually based. I got to know Energy Editors and  Journalists over time.  Then we lost the editors but now they are coming back. On a broader basis I like to follow energy aspects and in particular geo-politics affecting the producing and consuming regions, almost most of the world.  Too often now I feel I am reading too strong a personal bias in an article and therefore sometimes question what Iâ€™m reading! Of course, more so if the opinion differs from mine.  Overall though I enjoy the FT for its wide ranging coverage and the fact that it is far removed from the tabloid market!  I buy the digital version but before that came along I used to spend hours going through each edition.  In answer to the question, I feel the balance is right and Iâ€™m very happy with the content I receive

column3:
The New York Times has found great success in its non-news related content.  They have separate subscriptions available for NYT Cooking and Games.  The FT does an excellent job with its book reviews.  I would like to see more lifestyle related content such as food, travel, fashion, and music and entertainment.  The FT is particularly well positioned to take a more global perspective in these areas.  

I also think the FT could do a better job covering the huge world of podcasts and e-sports.  These are the primary forms of entertainment for a large number of future subscribers.  The lack of content in this area is a significant omission.

column3:
More analysis, critical voices and investigative journalism please. Less spurious ideological propaganda and rubberstamped press releases.

Good example: a cost-benefit analysis of the lockdown measures is something that only a publication of the FTâ€™s calibre can accomplish.

The overall quality of your editorial content  can be rather uneven ranging from (mostly) the worldâ€™s best to (sadly, increasingly often) rather questionable. Trying to persuade your generally centrist readership to accept extreme left ideology by commissioning very tendencious articles to interns is not a very good idea, Iâ€™m afraid. Especially at the time when the traditional media is going through a public trust crisis. 

The overzealous policing of the comments section and the regular purges, deletions  and shutdowns are deeply disturbing and very, very frustrating. It seems like your Community Editor Lucy Warwick-Ching is deeply dissatisfied with the FT readershipâ€™s opinions and tries to groom it to accept only her version of reality. It that really in her job description?

Anything that doesnâ€™t seem to agree with her chosen party line is ruthlessly eliminated. Any voice of disagreement is suppressed either by deleting comments or shutting down the discussion. I personally was blocked unless I would agree not to complain about the excessive censorship. My comments have been deleted, including those that achieved the highest recommended scores. I have observed that happening to many other people. That level of Stalinist vindictiveness doesnâ€™t belong in a serious newspaper like the FT and does a great disservice to your global brand.
Very happy with current content. No special requests.

column3: More integration of the human impact of business decisions.   For example, if the minimum wage is increased, more info on how that will impact a workerâ€™s financial health. The positive impact on the people who earn the wages, the members of society who work for the business, is generally glossed over.  To me, the FT seems uniquely capable of adding at least a little bit more of human side to the discussion.

Readers want truth, not leftwing or rightwing propaganda.
